(86,	1,	'2018-11-04 06:08:14',	'2018-11-04 06:08:14',	'FRIDAY 11 MAY 2018\r\n<blockquote><strong>â€œWell, i havenâ€™t finish processing yet, it was very intense, which was meant to be. It is obviously what it is, itâ€™s a film about death penalty, as much as it is about individual story.â€Â </strong>â€“ Audience Member</blockquote>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-9349 size-wide\" src=\"http://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/guilty_2-640x360.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs befits a film whose director and subject are both painters, the most striking images inÂ <em>GuiltyÂ </em>are of paint and ink marking surfaces. The first and most frequently recurring marks in the film are the brushstrokes on canvas of Myuran Sukumaran, the condemned â€˜Bali 9â€™ drug smuggler whose final 72 hours are dramatized in Sleethâ€™s debut documentary, which showed to a sold-out audience at the Human Rights Arts and Film Festival on Friday night. In a Q&amp;A session that preceded the screening, Sukumaranâ€™s lawyer, Julian McMahon AC, described how in prison the callow and selfish criminal transformed into a model prisonerâ€”an accomplished artist and a founder of educational programmes for his fellow inmates. Sleethâ€™s film shows Sukumaran (played in dramatic recreations by actor Adam McConvell) spending his final 72 hours painting self-portraits, an intense period of reckoning with his life and his identity as his execution nears.\r\n\r\nThe other defining mark in Sleethâ€™s visually striking film is theÂ <strong>XÂ </strong>target drawn over the heart of Sukumaran just before his execution. Despite all his effort to create a new life, the rehabilitated prisoner and artist cannot escape the death sentence handed down ten years earlier. The only victory that Sukumaran can manage is the â€˜escapeâ€™ of his paintings from death rowâ€”works which survive him and the seven other men executed with him and which, by testifying to lives