(115,	1,	'2018-11-04 12:13:14',	'2018-11-04 12:13:14',	'FRIDAY 11 MAY 2018\r\n<blockquote><strong>â€œWell, i havenâ€™t finish processing yet, it was very intense, which was meant to be. It is obviously what it is, itâ€™s a film about death penalty, as much as it is about individual story.â€Â </strong>â€“ Audience Member</blockquote>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-9349 size-wide\" src=\"http://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/guilty_2-640x360.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs befits a film whose director and subject are both painters, the most striking images inÂ <em>GuiltyÂ </em>are of paint and ink marking surfaces. The first and most frequently recurring marks in the film are the brushstrokes on canvas of Myuran Sukumaran, the condemned â€˜Bali 9â€™ drug smuggler whose final 72 hours are dramatized in Sleethâ€™s debut documentary, which showed to a sold-out audience at the Human Rights Arts and Film Festival on Friday night. In a Q&amp;A session that preceded the screening, Sukumaranâ€™s lawyer, Julian McMahon AC, described how in prison the callow and selfish criminal transformed into a model prisonerâ€”an accomplished artist and a founder of educational programmes for his fellow inmates. Sleethâ€™s film shows Sukumaran (played in dramatic recreations by actor Adam McConvell) spending his final 72 hours painting self-portraits, an intense period of reckoning with his life and his identity as his execution nears.\r\n\r\nThe other defining mark in Sleethâ€™s visually striking film is theÂ <strong>XÂ </strong>target drawn over the heart of Sukumaran just before his execution. Despite all his effort to create a new life, the rehabilitated prisoner and artist cannot escape the death sentence handed down ten years earlier. The only victory that Sukumaran can manage is the â€˜escapeâ€™ of his paintings from death rowâ€”works which survive him and the seven other men executed with him and which, by testifying to lives cut short by executionersâ€™ bullets, very powerfully tells a story that matters.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-10705 size-logo\" src=\"http://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/author-pic-150x150.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px\" srcset=\"https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/author-pic-150x150.jpg 150w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/author-pic-400x400.jpg 400w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/author-pic.jpg 480w\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><em>JimÂ McCormackÂ is a Melbourne-based academic and writer</em></strong>',	'GUILTY: THE LAST 72 HOURS OF SUKUMARANâ€™S LIFE',	'',	'inherit',	'closed',	'closed',	'',	'86-revision-v1',	'',	'',	'2018-11-04 12:13:14',	'2018-11-04 12:13:14',	'',	86,	'http://localhost:3157/watermelon/?p=115',	0,	'revision',	'',	0),
(116,	1,	'2018-11-04 12:14:16',	'2018-11-04 12:14:16',	'THURSDAY 10 MAY 2018\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-10627\" src=\"http://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/hraff-opening-night-48-640x360.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" srcset=\"https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/hraff-opening-night-48-400x267.jpg 400w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/hraff-opening-night-48-600x400.jpg 600w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/hraff-opening-night-48-768x512.jpg 768w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/hraff-opening-night-48-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/hraff-opening-night-48-225x150.jpg 225w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/hraff-opening-night-48-272x182.jpg 272w\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"600\" />\r\n\r\n<em><strong>Festival Correspondent Meg Hill gives her wrap up on Opening Night: After the Apology</strong></em>\r\n\r\nACMI was packed on Thursday night for the opening of the Human Rights Art and Film Festivalâ€™s (HRAFF) Melbourne leg. The opening of a festival implies a party atmosphere â€“ festival staff and patrons walking around with their mouths sneaking up at the corners in constant smiles. HRAFF is different. Thereâ€™s a buzz, thatâ€™s for sure, but itâ€™s a collective feeling ofÂ <i>readiness â€“Â </i>a ready to confront hard truths and create change. The opening night screened â€˜After the Apologyâ€™, part of the Indigenous program stream this year. In her pre-film speech Shareena Clanton warned the audience â€“ â€œIt wonâ€™t be comfortableâ€, and it wasnâ€™t.\r\n\r\n[embed]https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RwzP-bBZLUg[/embed]\r\n\r\nâ€˜After the Apologyâ€™ is the story of the forced removal of Indigenous children that continues today.Â Since Kevin Rudd formally apologised in 2008 for the stolen generations of the past, the number of Indigenous children forcibly removed from their families has almost doubled. There is no way to watch this film and feel comfortable. Itâ€™s devastating, but thatâ€™s the point. Shareena Clantonâ€™s speech made that clear when she told the audience â€œThis is about truth tellingâ€. For change to be made, people have to know. Thatâ€™s what HRAFF is about, communicating truth and knowledge to enact change.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIn a post film Q&amp;A, director Larissa Behrendt elaborated on the importance of self-determination â€“ a big theme within the film. Four grandmothers are the filmâ€™s protagonists, taking up their own self-determination and resistance when authorities donâ€™t honour the basic principle of an apology â€“ that you donâ€™t do it again. These are stories that matter. In the words of audience members interviewed on the night â€œThis is a film every single person in this country should seeâ€.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-logo wp-image-10599 alignleft\" src=\"http://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/portrait-150x150.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px\" srcset=\"https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/portrait-150x150.jpg 150w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/portrait.jpg 400w\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" />\r\n\r\nMeg Hill is a passionate Journalism student from Monash University &amp; a Journalist at Hyperlocal News.\r\n<em><a href=\"https://twitter.com/meg__hill\">Twitter</a>Â <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/meg-hill-703374b3/\">LinkedIn</a></em>',	'OPENING NIGHT WRAP UP â€“ HRAFF 2018',	'',	'inherit',	'closed',	'closed',	'',	'89-revision-v1',	'',	'',	'2018-11-04 12:14:16',	'2018-11-04 12:14:16',	'',	89,	'http://localhost:3157/watermelon/?p=116',	0,	'revision',	'',	0),
(117,	1,	'2018-11-04 12:16:02',	'2018-11-04 12:16:02',	'MONDAY 13 NOVEMBER 2017\r\n\r\nThe Human Rights Arts &amp; Film Festival been awarded the prestigious annual Graham F. Smith Peace Foundation Arts Prize, announced at the Peace Foundation Gala today. The prize is presented to one organization annually which has shown to make a contribution to peace through the arts.\r\n\r\nThe Human Rights Arts &amp; Film Festival was founded ten years ago to make human rights relevant, accessible and engaging to Australians through film, art, music and forums. It has since grown to become one of the countryâ€™s largest and most important human rights events. Since its inception, it has showcased over 479 films, 470 speakers, and 271 artists, musicians and performers, sharing inspiring human stories to over 100,000 attendees nationwide.\r\n\r\nThe Graham F. Smith Peace Foundation was founded in 1989 as a lasting legacy to its namesake. Graham F. Smith. Graham believed that people who are taught to think, challenge and are encouraged to expand their imagination, can create a better world. The purpose of the Foundation is the promotion of peace through all art forms that relate to human rights, social justice and environmental sustainability.\r\n\r\nâ€œGrahamâ€™s dedication to the egalitarian principles of socialism, democracy, peace, international understanding and the dignity of labour was the inspiration for the Peace Foundation that bears his name,â€ said Leonie Ebert, founding member of the Graham F Smith Peace Foundation. â€œWe believe the Human Rights Arts &amp; Film Festival embodies everything he stood for and has made a major contribution to peace in Australia, through the arts.â€\r\n\r\nâ€œWe are honoured to be an award recipient ofÂ the Graham Smith Peace Foundation Award,â€ saidÂ AletaÂ Moriarty, HRAFF CEO. â€œWe are driven to create a better, more peaceful world. We believe the arts, film and literature can help people connect with issues in a way nothing else can. And this is the first step in creating enduring change, changing peopleâ€™s hearts and minds.â€',	'HRAFF HAS BEEN AWARDED THE ANNUAL GRAHAM F. SMITH PEACE FOUNDATION ARTS AWARD',	'',	'publish',	'open',	'open',	'',	'hraff-has-been-awarded-the-annual-graham-f-smith-peace-foundation-arts-award',	'',	'',	'2018-11-04 13:17:24',	'2018-11-04 13:17:24',	'',	0,	'http://localhost:3157/watermelon/?p=117',	0,	'post',	'',	0),
(118,	1,	'2018-11-04 12:16:40',	'2018-11-04 12:16:40',	'WEDNESDAY 3 MAY 2017\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<div class=\"gmail_quote\">\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<div>\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<div class=\"gmail_quote\">\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<h4>If You Were Moved My Our 2017 FilmÂ <strong><a href=\"http://2018.hraff.org.au/events/dheepan/\">Dheepan</a></strong>, This Is The Event For You! Learn More About Sri Lankan Culture Through Delicious Tamil Fare.</h4>\r\nà®µà®¿à®°à¯à®¨à¯à®¤à¯Â Tamil Feasts is a social enterprise supporting recently settled asylum seekers through the celebration of foodÂ and culture. Serving up traditional Sri Lankan fare prepared by Tamil men currently seeking asylum in Australia, these thrice-weekly feasts create a context in which the cooks are able to share the food heritage of their Sri Lankan homeland with the wider community. This unique enterprise simultaneously creates a space in which Australians are able to show their support of individuals who are presently undergoing the difficult experience of seeking refuge in a foreign land â€“ all the while partaking in some seriously tasty food! HRAFF spoke to Dori Ellington from the Ceres Tamil Feasts to find out more about this exciting venture.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div><strong>Could you please give us a brief rundown of what happens at the Tamil Feasts?</strong></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\nTamil Feasts is a big dinner party 3 nights a week. Niro, Nirma, Sri and NIgethan cook up traditional Sri Lankan fare and serve it to diners who pre book. It is 3 course meal â€“ starters, then a thali plate with a main curry, side curry, dahl, salad, chutney, sambal, papadum and rice, and finished with dessert. The guys share some of their story as well â€“ life in Sri Lanka, seeking asylum, 6 Â½ years in Australian detention centres, and settling into the Melbourne community.\r\n\r\n<strong>When and why did the idea for Tamil Feasts first come about?</strong>\r\n\r\nWhen Sri and Nirma were released, after 6 Â½ years in detention, they struggled to find work. We got together and thought, â€œHey lets have a feastâ€, tickets went online for 2 feasts and sold out within a week. For 4 months, we held weekly feasts on Tuesday nights â€“ always selling out ages in advance. Then Niro was released and we started catering more, and we got Bhaji added to our menu and more Tamil love songs were played. Â Then Nigethan was released and we added seafood and meat to our menu, and added another night!Â NowÂ Tamil Feasts are 3 nights a week â€“ often selling out well in advance.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-square wp-image-8630 aligncenter\" src=\"http://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/unnamed-480x400.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"480\" height=\"400\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Dheepan</em>, showing this year at HRAFF, examines the experience of a Sri Lankan woman as she moves to Paris, and the violence that she suffers there. How does an initiative like Tamil Feasts help prevent such violence and make that transition easier/better for both asylum seekers and the wider community?</strong>\r\n\r\nWe think initiatives like Tamil Feasts ease the transition and make it better for everyone â€“ both asylum seekers and the wider community because it creates a space for interaction and allows for people to interact. We are able to tell our story and people are able to show their support or to ask questions or to introduce people who do not know where they stand to people seeking asylum. Tamil Feasts lets people see the people behind the politics, behind the fear mongering, behind the lables, behind what holds us back from realizing that we are all people doing our best.\r\n\r\n<strong>From what we hear, none of the chefs behind Tamil Feasts, Nirma, Sri, Niro and Nigethan,Â were chefs by trade back in Sri Lanka, despite their ability to create absolutely delicious food â€“Â has there been much of a learning curve in terms of serving large numbers of people and other challenges that come with preparing the feasts?</strong>\r\n\r\nNo, not really. Tamil culture is all about communal eating and feeding big groups! So serving big numbers has come easy â€“ but if there are ever any questions about a recipe one of the guys is quickly making phone calls to their mom/grandmother/sister back in Sri Lanka for advice.\r\n\r\n<strong>Do you have an especially rewarding or surprising memory from the initiative that you could share with us?</strong>\r\n\r\nEvery night! As corny as that sounds it is the truth! We are still crazy over-joyed and overwhelmed that 3 nights a week we get packed houses coming to eat our food and coming to hear our stories! We were only supposed to have one or 2 feasts and now its almost been 2 years!! We are constantly surprised by the joy, the compassion and the overwhelming kindness that people bring to Tamil Feasts.\r\n\r\n<strong>It seems like the feasts have received a great response so far. Do you and the chefs have plans for the future?</strong>\r\n\r\nWe have so many plansâ€¦ too many plans! We just launched a Chai brand with 2 different flavours â€œWelcomeâ€™ and â€œFriendshipâ€ and a Catering menu. So we will focus on feeding people 3 nights a week, getting our Chai out there, and more cateringâ€¦. But there will be more.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-8631 size-full\" src=\"http://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/unnamed-2.jpg\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" srcset=\"https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/unnamed-2.jpg 300w, https://2018.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/unnamed-2-213x150.jpg 213w\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"211\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Book your Tamil Feast experienceÂ <a href=\"https://www.trybooking.com/book/event?embed&amp;eid=251700\">here</a>. For more information, visitÂ <a href=\"http://www.tamilfeasts.ceres.org.au/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" data-saferedirecturl=\"https://www.google.com/url?hl=en-GB&amp;q=http://www.tamilfeasts.ceres.org.au&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1493857701509000&amp;usg=AFQjCNE_P1WLSBG4l4KShF-CgULMz4efkw\">www.tamilfeasts.ceres.org.au</a>Â </em><em>or contactÂ <a href=\"mailto:tamilfeasts@ceres.org.au\">tamilfeasts@ceres.org.au</a>.</em>',	'MOVED BY DHEEPAN? CHECK OUT CERES TAMIL FEASTS.',	'',	'publish',	'open',	'open',	'',	'moved-by-dheepan-check-out-ceres-tamil-feasts',	'',	'',	'2018-11-04 12:18:36',	'2018-11-04 12:18:36',	'',	0,	'http://localhost:3157/watermelon/?p=118',	0,	'post',	'',	0),
