(147,	1,	'2018-11-04 12:39:54',	'2018-11-04 12:39:54',	'<div id=\"post-header\">\r\n<p class=\"post-date\">TUESDAY 19 APRIL 2016</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nAs always, HRAFF are proudly celebrating women in film and this year we have an incredibly strong line-up of female champions, including:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/chasingasylum\">Chasing Asylum</a>Â â€“Â Eva Orner (Australia)</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-5605 alignright\" src=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/eva_orner_087-copy_lucas_allen-print.jpg\" alt=\"Eva Orner Filmmaker\" width=\"150\" height=\"210\" />Ornerâ€™s previous works includeÂ includeÂ <i>Untold Desires</i>Â (Best Documentary at the Australian Film Institute Awards, the Logie Awards and the Australian Human Rights Awards) andÂ <i>Strange Fits of Passion</i>Â (nominated for the Criticsâ€™ Award at the Cannes Film Festival). Orner won an Academy Award and an Emmy for theÂ 2007 documentary about US military torture that she produced,Â <em>Taxi To The Dark Side</em>. Remaining aware of Australian current affairs whilst living in the US for a decade, Orner was compelled to act and return home to explore Australiaâ€™s treatment of asylum seekers in the film Chasing Asylum.\r\n\r\nâ€œAs a filmmaker, this is the sort of work I do, and I thought I canâ€™t just keep watching this, I have to do something,â€ she said via Skype to theÂ <em><a href=\"http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/oscar-winner-eva-orner-turns-to-crowdfunding-for-asylum-seeker-film-bloody-unaustralian-20140528-zrqfo.html#ixzz46EOLepfP\">Sydney Morning Herald</a></em>.\r\n\r\nEva Orner will participate in a post-film Q&amp;A at theÂ <a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/chasingasylummelbourne/\">Melbourne</a>,Â <a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/chasingasylumalice/\">Alice Springs,</a>Â <a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/chasingasylumdarwin/\">Darwin</a>Â andÂ <a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/chasingasylumperth/\">Perth</a>Â screenings.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/they-will-have-to-kill-us-first/\">They Will Have to Kill Us First</a>Â â€“Â Johanna Schwartz (UK)</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignright wp-image-6091\" src=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/screen-shot-2016-04-19-at-11.59.19-am.png\" alt=\"Women in Film Johanna Schwartz\" width=\"141\" height=\"210\" />Johanna SchwartzÂ has produced and directed films for broadcasters includingÂ the BBC, Channel 4, Channel 5, Discovery, National Geographic, The History Channel, PBS, CNBC, CNN and MTV. She works internationally with a particular focus on Africa.\r\n\r\nâ€œI am so proud to bring these musicianâ€™s stories to the world. Theyâ€™ve been through hell, and survived to sing about it. Though the conflict in Mali is still far from over, with extremist attacks continuing in the north and south to this day, I have no doubt that these musicians will continue to stand up and fight for their right to sing.â€ â€“ Johanna Schwartz\r\n\r\nJohanna Schwartz joins us via Skype at theÂ <a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/they-will-have-to-kill-us-first/\">Melbourne</a>Â andÂ <a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/they-will-have-to-kill-us-first-sydney/\">Sydney</a>Â screenings.\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/mallory/\">Mallory</a>Â â€“Â Helena TÅ™eÅ¡tÃ­kovÃ¡ (Czech Republic)</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignright wp-image-6089\" src=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/helenan.jpg\" alt=\"Female Filmmakers Helena TÅ™eÅ¡tÃ­kovÃ¡\" width=\"140\" height=\"210\" />Respected filmmaker TÅ™eÅ¡tÃ­kovÃ¡, has made over fifty documentariesÂ in her career, often investing many years in her subjects. SheÂ specialises in time-lapse projects that chronicle peopleâ€™s life stories on long-term basis, andÂ <em>Mallory</em>Â is no exception. Over 13 years Trestikova followedÂ the life of Mallory,Â a recovered drug addict faced with the challenges of homelessness, unemployment and depression.\r\n\r\nâ€œAs in Trestikovaâ€™s other work, the helmerâ€™s sincere interest in her subject whittles away whatever prejudice audiences might have toward addicts, thieves, outcasts and other so-called â€œlosers.â€ Instead, we come away from her films sensitive to the fact that had fateâ€™s whims wafted another way, we could conceivably find ourselves in her subjectsâ€™ shoes.â€ â€“Â <em><a href=\"http://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/mallory-film-review-1201540545/\">Variety</a></em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/hooligan-sparrow/\">Hooligan Sparrow</a>Â â€“Â Nanfu Wang (China/America)</strong>\r\n\r\n<em><img class=\"alignright wp-image-6093\" src=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/hooligansparrow-nanfu-wang-500x500-e1461031958848.jpg\" alt=\"hooligansparrow-nanfu-wang-500x500\" width=\"150\" height=\"205\" />Hooligan Sparrow</em>, the story of the titular Chinese womenâ€™s rights activist, is the feature debut of Sundance and IFP-supported filmmaker and Sundance Documentary Fund recipient, Nanfu Wang.\r\n\r\nâ€œI followed Sparrow with my camera, eventually becoming a target myself: Chinese national security agents harassed my family, intimidated my friends and summoned me for interrogation.â€ â€“ Nanfu Wang\r\n\r\nDirectorÂ Nanfu Wang will join us via Skype post-film.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/gtfo/\">GTFO</a>Â â€“Â Shannon Sun-Higginson (USA)</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"wp-image-6094 alignright\" src=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/sunhig-e1461032643370.png\" alt=\"sunhig\" width=\"150\" height=\"202\" />Sun-Higginsonâ€™sÂ first feature documentaryÂ <em>GTFO</em>, about women in the video game industry, was inspired by the harassment she observed in the live-streaming competition, Cross Assault. The film was funded onÂ Kickstarter and premiered at SXSWÂ 2015.\r\n\r\nâ€œMy biggest fear for this movie is that it scares young women away from this industry, which is really growing and thriving right now,â€ Ms. Sun-Higginson said to theÂ <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/08/movies/in-the-documentary-gtfo-female-video-gamers-fight-back.html?_r=0\">New York Times</a>. â€œObviously the more women and the more diverse people in general who join the industry, the better.â€\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSee also:\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/driving-with-selvi/\">Driving With Selvi</a>Â â€“Â Elisa Paloschi (Canada)</strong>\r\n\r\nThere will be a post-film Q&amp;A with Director Elisa Paloschi.\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/call-me-dad/\">Call Me Dad</a>Â â€“Â Sophie Wiesner (Australia)</strong>\r\n\r\nThere will be a post-film Q&amp;A with Director Sophie Wiesner.\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/flocking/\">Flocking</a>Â â€“Â Beata GÃ¥rdeler (Sweden)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/maya-angelou/\">Maya Angelou And Still I Rise</a>Â â€“Â Rita Coburn-Whack (w Bob Hercules) (USA)\r\n</strong><strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/drone/\">Drone</a>Â â€“Â Tonje Hessen Schei (Norway)\r\n</strong><strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/censored-voices/\">Censored Voices</a>Â â€“Â Mor Loushy (Israel)\r\n</strong><strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/armor-of-light/\">TheÂ Armor of Light</a>Â â€“Â Abigail Disney and Kathleen Hughes (USA)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe also have a huge contingent of Australian and international female short filmmakers, including:\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/international-shorts-war-conflict/\">The Face of the Ukraine: Casting Oksana BaiulÂ </a>â€“Â Kitty Green (Australia)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/australian-shorts/\">Workmate</a>Â â€“Â Genevieve Clay-Smith (Australia)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/australian-shorts/\">In My Shoes</a>Â â€“Â Monique Schafter (Australia)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/australian-shorts/\">Symphony of Strange Waters</a>Â â€“Â Saba Vasefi (Australia)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/australian-shorts/\">Naji</a>Â â€“Â Kimberley West (Australia)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/australian-shorts/\">Bluey</a>Â â€“Â Darlene Johnson (Australia)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/international-shorts/\">A Few Seconds</a>Â â€“Â Nora El Hourch (France/Morocco)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/international-shorts/\">Listen</a>Â â€“Â Rungano Nyoni (Zambia)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/international-shorts-love-intimacy/\">Maman(s)</a>Â â€“Â MaÃ¯mouna DoucourÃ© (France)</strong>\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/event/international-shorts-love-intimacy/\">Letting You Go</a>Â â€“Â Kim Faber (The Netherlands)</strong>\r\n\r\nAside from the femaleâ€™s working behind the scenes, we also have a number of films centred around female driven roles.\r\n<a href=\"http://2016.hraff.org.au/program/#topic=women\">Browse these in our program</a>.',	'HRAFF: PROUDLY SUPPORTING WOMEN IN FILM',	'',	'inherit',	'closed',	'closed',	'',	'135-revision-v1',	'',	'',	'2018-11-04 12:39:54',	'2018-11-04 12:39:54',	'',	135,	'http://localhost:3157/watermelon/?p=147',	0,	'revision',	'',	0),
